note.p: On this form of aer see Ronald Black (1973): 205-06.

Collui here is understood to be the anthroponym Colla but due to markup rules a proper name cannot be part of a compound word. To allow for a better reading, Collui has not been marked up a proper name here.

There is a diagonal stroke attached to the top of the final i in this word. As the ink is much heavier than a usual acute accent, the present editor postulates that it to be a mark that arose as the scribe realised he was about to write a character other than what he intended and consequently connected it to the i to make an í.

note.p: Black (1973) gives this as 'fann' but there is clearly a supercript a over the f. The present editor wonderw might the missing portion of MS had an i and whether this may consequently be be a form of ifern/ifrinn.

Black (0111317) and (1973, pp.201, 208) notes this as 'rugadh' and nowhere notes that the reading in the MS is is 'slugadh' and that his reading is thus an emendation. The present editor is nonetheless inclined to agree with such an emendation.
Black (0120113) gives the headword sár- but says this is doubtful.

Black (0031094) gives the headword here as càlaidh but the sense is unclear. While the present also had difficulties with this, they are of the opinion that a genitive of calla, 'hood', Cála is given as a form of this word in Dinneen and it is possible that "a cowled knight" is the sense intended here.

The final character of this line is indistinct and be a c or o. Neither of these, however, would render a word which makes sense in this context. The scribe employs different forms of the letter d and the form here could also be a d similar to that in the word íad on line 18 of this page. The present editor believes that readng this character as a d, is the possibility that most sense, i.e. the particle indaas inflected for the 3pl as in older periods of the language.

Given the scribe's practice so far this is likely to have been intended to be enclosing puncta to indicate the abbreviation. AS is however, the abbreviation has been noted as a single punctum and the abbreviation has been expanded after the g rather than before it.
There is a punctum delens above the suspension stroke here but it is unclear to the present editor how this could fit in here.
